DropoutGuard — Users, Roles, Responsibilities, and How They Create Each Other
================================================================================

This document explains:
1) Which user roles exist in the system
2) What each role does
3) How roles create each other (the registration/creation chain)
4) The data-ownership rules enforced by the backend (who can see/manage which records)


1) Roles in the system
-----------------------
The backend uses these roles:
- superadmin
- sector_leader
- headmaster
- dos
- teacher


2) Role responsibilities (what they do)
----------------------------------------

2.1 superadmin
- Creates sector_leader accounts.
- Has global visibility (can view all active data depending on endpoint logic).
- Can toggle activation (activate/deactivate) for users they can manage (depending on UI/API scoping).


2.2 sector_leader
- Creates schools.
- Creates headmaster accounts.
- Views KPI/report data for schools created by them.


2.3 headmaster
- Creates DOS (dos) accounts for their school.
- Views student attendance and risk KPIs for their school.
- Can view/manage roster and drill down into school data (scoped to their school).


2.4 dos (DOS)
- Creates teacher accounts.
- Ensures teachers have classes (roster/class assignment is represented by the Class model with a teacher_id).
- Manages student lists for teachers/classes in their school:
  - Add a student into a specific teacher’s class list
  - “Delete” students via soft delete (is_active = False)
  - Upload/replace students via CSV (DOS-only)


2.5 teacher
- Completes daily attendance + dropout-risk form for students assigned to their class.
- Submits data to the ML prediction pipeline and stores prediction results per student per day.
- Sees dashboards limited to their assigned class.


3) How roles create each other (creation chain)
-------------------------------------------------
The intended hierarchy/creation flow in this codebase is:

superadmin
  → creates sector_leader accounts

sector_leader
  → creates schools
  → creates headmaster accounts

headmaster
  → creates DOS (dos) accounts

dos
  → creates teacher accounts
  → assigns teachers to classes (represented by Class.teacher_id; teacher can only access that class)

teacher
  → does not create other users in this app flow
  → creates Attendance records by submitting daily attendance/risk forms


4) Data ownership & access rules (how “who can do what” is enforced)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
The backend enforces access using role checks and ownership fields such as:
- user.role
- user.school_id (for school-scoped roles)
- school.created_by_id (sector_leader ownership)
- Class.teacher_id (teacher/class assignment)


4.1 Teacher access scope
- A teacher can only access students whose class_id belongs to the Class assigned to that teacher.
- When saving attendance, the backend checks:
  - student.class_id matches the teacher’s assigned class

Relevant routes:
- GET  /api/attendance/student/<student_id>
- POST /api/attendance/student/<student_id>


4.2 DOS/Headmaster student access scope
- DOS and headmaster can access students only within their own school (student.school_id must match current_user.school_id).

Relevant routes:
- GET  /api/attendance/risk-frequency
- GET  /api/attendance/student/<student_id>/risk-factors
- Student list and management endpoints:
  - /api/dos-teachers-students/<teacher_id>/students
  - /api/dos-teachers-students/<teacher_id>/students/add
  - /api/dos-teachers-students/<teacher_id>/students/<student_id> (soft delete)


4.3 Sector leader access scope
- Sector leader can only access schools they created (School.created_by_id == current_user.id).
- Student lists and KPIs for the sector are derived by collecting student.school_id values for those schools.

Relevant routes:
- GET /api/attendance/risk-frequency
- GET /api/reports/sector/<sector_leader_id> (used by Dashboard for sector leader)


4.4 Student lifecycle (soft delete)
- “Deleting” a student does not remove the row; it sets student.is_active = False.
- CSV import and roster replacement reactivate/overwrite via class_id + school_id and is_active toggling.

Relevant behavior:
- DELETE /api/dos-teachers-students/<teacher_id>/students/<student_id>
- POST /api/students/import-csv (DOS-only)
- CSV “replace” deactivates existing active students for that class


5) Summary: who creates what
------------------------------
- superadmin creates: sector_leader
- sector_leader creates: school, headmaster
- headmaster creates: dos
- dos creates: teacher, and manages teacher class student lists
- teacher creates: Attendance (daily attendance/risk submissions) for assigned students


